Bunch of lore missed. Kirby doesn't destroy what he consumes, but stores it internally, forever, in some form of stasis. He has the ability to retrieve from this micro-universe an ability (copying), energy, and sometimes the original item, unchanged. Also, he is a baby of his species, explaining his simplistic nature.


As for the power/complexity dichotomy, there is none. One of the simpliest objects in our universe are black holes, which are also some of the most powerful.

snippet.textDisplay:
Brian, great work exploring what Kirby is, or more specifically, what he needs to be, which is technically nothing at all, but if I can add my two sense, I think it's clear based on your criteria exactly what Kirby is. Kirby is imagination, more specifically childlike imagination, perhaps even babyish levels of it.

Imagination doesn't want anything, if we manifest it as a being, it most likely would have few to no needs at all besides the ones it sets for itself (sleeping and eating). Imagination doesn't have its own voice, it inherits other voices, so the need for one becomes obsolete (doesn't speak). We don't know the origins of our imaginations, of the fundamental process of creating non-reality, so that explains that (origins). Similarly, imagination is impartial, neither cruel or polite, always giving you something from below consciousness (lack of emotional intelligence). Finally, Kirby is shaped like a friend. For many, imagination is a great friend, a tried companion, the source of every book and movie and story. Imagination, however, requires shaping. Hugging it does little to create anything at all, so you have to temper it to make it useful, but it can be there for you even if you don't need anything from it.

That leads us to the discussion on Kirby's power level. Imagination often is used to face fears, fears that it can destroy as it consumes them (destroys what it consumes). Imagination gives you whatever powers you need, sometimes even ones you request, see lucid dreaming, giving Kirby the ability to have any skill base he wants whenever he wants them (skilled technician). Kirby can be anything. (I don't think I have to explain that one). Kirby's enemies are cosmic horrors. Perhaps, it's better to say that Kirby's enemies are, *cough cough*, nightmares, things that can feel insurmountable at the time but in the realm of imagination often fall with little more than a big hammer to whack them on the head with (cosmic horrors). And, as your last point, Kirby's infinite power. Imagination doesn't ever seem to need rest or sleep. Maybe it does when we don't need it but rarely more than that. Imagination is the well that never runs dry, more and more creative content, like these videos here, is created, spoken into existence. Imagination is the only place where this kind of infinite power could reside, giving him all that makes him what he is.

He is, as you say, "nothing and everything". Thanks for reading!

snippet.textDisplay: Kirby represents the zenith of capitalistic hubris. He consumes everything, leaving nothing behind. In his wake, trails of nothingness—not even one dead body. The folly of the capitalist is exactly the same: once a product has been consumed it returns to nothingness. Can the toy you played with as a child, sitting in the dark recesses of your basement closet, truly be considered alive anymore? Or how about that book you picked up at the checkout line at Barnes and Noble? “Thus Spoke Zarathustra” or something like that? You don’t remember either—you just wanted to impress the cute cashier lady. But you get home, place the book on your bedside table and plan on doing some light reading before you go to bed. But you’ve never done light reading and you never will. Had you read that book, you would understand. You would understand Nietzsche was onto something. Perhaps God is actually dead after all. What God could allow Kirby, the manifestation of human greed in puffball form, to exist? He will continue to consume until a void of nothingness is all that remains. Are we really so different?

snippet.textDisplay: Kirby represents the mental state of the average person in the midst of playing an action game. The id, the part of our mind that directs our basic needs such as eating, sleeping, and jumping swiftly away from enemies who are trying to kill us, is given the front seat, while our more sophisticated faculties, such as our ability to pilot giant mechs, are relegated to a support role that isn't given a tremendous amount of focus.  Kirby is a vehicle for us.

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, I’ve made a discovery. August 2, 2019 was in between the almost 2 month haitus of Unraveled, so this was why there was such a long break between his BotW cooking video and his Pet HP video. Furthermore, the Pet HP video starts with Brian saying ‘Is life quantifiable?’ Which is clearly referencing his insanity over Kirby’s origin.

But wait, there’s more! January 15th also makes sense! This is because he was driven so insane not just by Kirby’s origin, but by his realisation that he is a Luigi and not a Waluigi. Assuming that in the UCU (Unraveled Cinematic Universe) Brian runs off after the release of the Waluigi video, around Christmas. Which gives him 3 weeks to build that beard and moustache.

Thank you for coming to my TED Talk.

snippet.textDisplay:
He is a sentient black hole. Matter cannot be destroy after all, but can be transported, that's why smash characters can be transported nearby, since he is smart enough to know its a sort of competition, while on other games he just transports his enemies farther away so they don't stay on his way.
Edit: Black holes are generally shaped as circles as well, since he is pretty much a natural phenomena that cannot be stopped, its natural for higher sentient beings to be afraid of him, since they may be able to tame him but not able to stop him. Nature can and should probably be seen as a friend since it doesn't do anything out of malice just like Kirby, the copy ability is probably a result of the space time dilatation that occurs near black holes, aka when the enemy is sort of traveling though the black hole, when the enemy can be seen sort of, which explain why eventually Kirby always goes back to his normal form. Him being pink doesn't matter since at the end of the day we see colors through eyes designed a certain way and other creatures may look at him and see different colors, also it could just be colorized just like when NASA put some colors on their pictures so its easier to understand (and pretty).
